    "PAGE EIGHT E H S REPORTS FROM WASHINGTON House HorseTrading DualVictory For Dixie Civil Right Labor Bill Spotlight In 6O On House Washington D C The smashing defeat which a coali Von of conservative Republicans and Southern Democrats hand ed the Democratic leadership and industrial state congressmen in ramming through the tough est of several pending labor bills in the House was delivered at the expense of new civil rights legislation Many Southerners would have unquestionably voted for the LandrumGriffin Labor Reform bill anyway But the nearsolid Dixie bloc vote handed to House Minority Leader Charles A Hal leck was not delivered without retribution Long before the test vote was actually taken on the Landrum Griffin Bill sponsored by Democratic Rep Phil Landrum of Georgia and Republican Rep Robert Griffin of Michigan the sponsors knew they had the votes to win The day before the test vote on the measure the vote by which the House tentatively agreed to the provisions of the LandrumGriffin bill Con gressman Landrum told a Geor gia radio audience he would win by over 20 votes When the tally was taken the Landrum Griffin forces had won by 29 votes The story behind the victory"
